messages.text:
Hey folks, Congress introduced two companion bills that could affect us aspiring data scientists: the “Local Zoning Decisions Protection Act of 2017,” will eliminate the data to support social change: "SEC. 3. PROHIBITION ON USE OF FEDERAL FUNDS. 
Notwithstanding any other provision of law, no Federal funds may be used to design, build, maintain, utilize, or provide access to a Federal database of geospatial information on community racial disparities or disparities in access to affordable housing." What and how we measure affects the policies we implement! Check out the bill here: <https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/senate-bill/103/text> and if you want to stay in the loop, I hear these folks are keeping tabs on this type of shenanigan <http://www.ppehlab.org/>

"Think of machine learning algorithms as an armory packed with axes, sword, blades, bow, dagger etc. You have various tools, but you ought to learn to use them at the right time. As an analogy, think of ‘Regression’ as a sword capable of slicing and dicing data efficiently, but incapable of dealing with highly complex data. On the contrary, ‘Support Vector Machines’ is like a sharp knife – it works on smaller datasets, but on them, it can be much more stronger and powerful in building models." :thinking_face: :joy:
